JSX stands for JavaScript XML. It allows us to write HTML inside JavaScript and place them in the DOM without using functions like appendChild( ) or createElement( ). As stated in the official docs of React, JSX provides syntactic sugar for React.createElement( ) function. Note- We can create react applications without using JSX as well. Note- We can create react applications without using JSX as well. Let’s understand how JSX works: how JSX works Without using JSX, we would have to create an element by the following process: const text = React.createElement('p', {}, 'This is a text');
const container = React.createElement('div','{}',text );
ReactDOM.render(container,rootElement); const text = React.createElement('p', {}, 'This is a text');
const container = React.createElement('div','{}',text );
ReactDOM.render(container,rootElement); Using JSX, the above code can be simplified: Using JSX const container = (
<div>
  <p>This is a text</p>
</div>
);
ReactDOM.render(container,rootElement); const container = (
<div>
  <p>This is a text</p>
</div>
);
